// tele_spec_proto — the stages 1-2 file for EFFECT_BOOTSTRAP_PLAN.md (kernel
// signature, floor handler, tele_spec). SEEDED (2026-07-07) with hazard 1a's
// empirical pins: the stage-1 mint clause must hand a continuation to the
// bind_hyp route, and CLAUDE.md's compiler-workarounds section documents that
// a continuation passed THROUGH a function miscompiles under nested binders
// (the fresh hyp leaks into the result and trips the escape check). These pins
// establish, on the live compiler, which shapes are actually safe:
//
//   control     inline lambdas at the route (the tele_walk shape) — safe;
//   mint_via    the continuation as a helper PARAMETER, passed on unapplied —
//               the documented wall's minimal form;
//   mint_naive  the innocent wrapper {h} -> kont h — bracket abstraction's
//               eta rule collapses it back to the bare parameter;
//   go_letbound the continuation as a mid-body `let`, closed over the OUTER
//               hyp — the shape the historical miscompile was observed in;
//   mint_keep   {h} -> kont (keep h), keep a top-level identity — the inner
//               application blocks the eta, and keep arriving as a scope
//               literal (not the CIR `I` sentinel) blocks the S (K p) I
//               collapse (the plan's keep trick);
//   floor_rec   the clause as a RECORD field (the stage-1 handler shape);
//   mint_loop   the continuation references a fix `self` and reaches the
//               route through a helper (the walker's historical context).
//
// Every continuation body below USES the outer hyp (`t a b`), the dataflow
// that historically failed, and returns a hyp-free verdict (no real escape).
//
// FINDING (2026-07-07): the documented miscompile does NOT reproduce in any
// of these forms — all ten pins pass on the live compiler. Either an
// intervening compiler change fixed it (candidates: the 2026-06-12 match
// desugar closing the cut over arm free vars; the 2026-07-05 let rework), or
// the failure needed a context these minimal forms still miss. Consequences:
// the stage-1 mint clause can be written in the natural shape
// `{ty, resume} -> param_apply (bind_hyp ty) resume` (mint_via IS that
// clause, pinned nested + fix-self + record-field); the keep trick works and
// stays available if an unpinned context fails; and this file is the
// regression guard either way. CLAUDE.md's inline-lambda rule stays the law
// for KERNEL code (tele_walk's inline mint is not relaxed by these pins).
// Baseline (rust-eager-native, 2026-07-07): ~21s wall, 10 pins.
open use "../kernel/prelude.disp"

// control: inline continuations, nested binders — the safe shape:
test param_apply (bind_hyp Tree) ({a} -> param_apply (bind_hyp Tree) ({b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b)))) = Ok true

// the helper parameter pass (unapplied):
let mint_via := {ty, kont} -> param_apply (bind_hyp ty) kont
test mint_via Tree ({a} -> Ok (is_fork (t t a))) = Ok true
test mint_via Tree ({a} -> mint_via Tree ({b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b)))) = Ok true

// the eta-trap wrapper (collapses to the bare parameter):
let mint_naive := {ty, kont} -> param_apply (bind_hyp ty) ({h} -> kont h)
test mint_naive Tree ({a} -> mint_naive Tree ({b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b)))) = Ok true

// the mid-body let-bound continuation over the outer hyp:
test param_apply (bind_hyp Tree) ({a} -> {
  let go := {b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b))
  param_apply (bind_hyp Tree) go
}) = Ok true

// the keep trick (the stage-1 mint clause shape):
let keep := {x} -> x
let mint_keep := {ty, kont} -> param_apply (bind_hyp ty) ({h} -> kont (keep h))
test mint_keep Tree ({a} -> Ok (is_fork (t t a))) = Ok true
test mint_keep Tree ({a} -> mint_keep Tree ({b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b)))) = Ok true
test param_apply (bind_hyp Tree) ({a} -> {
  let go := {b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b))
  param_apply (bind_hyp Tree) ({h} -> go (keep h))
}) = Ok true

// the clause as a record field (how the stage-1 floor handler will carry it):
let floor_rec := { on_mint := {ty, kont} -> param_apply (bind_hyp ty) ({h} -> kont (keep h)) }
test (floor_rec.on_mint) Tree ({a} -> (floor_rec.on_mint) Tree ({b} -> Ok (is_fork (t a b)))) = Ok true

// the closest repro of the HISTORICAL context: the continuation references a
// fix `self` (the walker's shape — "a continuation {h} -> self ... h passed
// THROUGH a function") and reaches the route through the helper. This is the
// exact dataflow the stage-1 handler has (handle's fold hands the clause a
// resume that closes over the fold's self):
let mint_loop := fix ({self, n, acc} ->
  if (tree_eq n zero) then (Ok acc)
  else (mint_via Tree ({h} -> self (nat_pred n) (is_fork (t acc h)))))
test mint_loop 2 t = Ok true
